<br>
I know who he is and I know he left.  <br>
<br>
The game is old.  The staleness of the game comes from an old game that is has gone beyond it's intended life.  The limits of the game engine (not to mention from what I hear a poorly programmed one) has hindered the developers to what they can and cannot do.  <br>
<br>
I'm not sayin' that McQuaid is a genius or not...  but all he did was take a few top muds and add some 3D graphics.  Many of the ideas were straight rip-offs.  <br>
<br>
In addition--while many parts of the game have been worn out and diluted, not to mention some really dumb changes, there have been many positives added to the game since some (not all) of the founders left to form the new start-up at MicroSoft.  I'm curious to see how his project at MicroSoft turns out.  EQ might have been a lucky one-hit wonder for all we know... <br>
<br>
Anyway...  if my memory serves me correctly, Verant was an offshoot of 989 studios.  They have always been a part of Sony.  They were never really &quot;taken over&quot; by Sony.  It was just a name change...  Although, I will gladly admist that I may be mistaken--it's been a bit since I've last been to San Diego.  <br>
<br>
Back to the topic on hand.  I will agree that Sony has made many poor long-term customer relation decisions in my opinion with their SoE division.  A bunch of shortcuts and rushed products has really tarnished their reputation.  Although their short-term business decisions have been pretty solid.  These guys are selling a ton of software and rackin' in month after month of subscription fees.  <br>
<br>
